  "prompt": "How fast can helicopters travel?",
  "response": "The speed of helicopters can vary significantly depending on their design, purpose, and engine power. Here are some general speed ranges for different types of helicopters:\n\n1. **Civil Helicopters**: Typically, civil helicopters used for transportation, tourism, or emergency services have a cruising speed of **130 to 160 mph (210 to 260 km/h)**. Examples include the Bell 206 JetRanger and the Airbus H125.\n\n2. **Military Helicopters**: Military helicopters are often faster due to their advanced technology and power. Their speeds range from **150 to 200 mph (240 to 320 km/h)**. The UH-60 Black Hawk, for instance, has a cruising speed of around 175 mph (280 km/h).\n\n3. **Attack Helicopters**: Attack helicopters, such as the AH-64 Apache, are designed for speed and agility. They can reach speeds of up to **185 mph (300 km/h)**.\n\n4. **Experimental/Record-Holding Helicopters**: Some specialized or experimental helicopters have achieved much higher speeds. For example, the Eurocopter X3 (now Airbus Helicopters) reached a top speed of **293 mph (472 km/h)** in 2013 during a test flight.\n\n### Factors Affecting Helicopter Speed:\n- **Rotor Design**: The shape and configuration of the rotor blades influence speed.\n- **Engine Power**: More powerful engines can push a helicopter to higher speeds.\n- **Aerodynamics**: Streamlined designs reduce drag, increasing speed.\n- **Weight**: Heavier helicopters often have lower maximum speeds.\n\n### Range vs. Speed:\nHelicopters are not as fast as fixed-wing aircraft, which can travel at much higher speeds. However, helicopters excel in maneuverability and are capable of vertical takeoff and landing (VTOL), making them invaluable in many applications despite their relatively lower speeds.",
